China Stocks: Air China, China Eastern, FAW Car, SAIC Motor

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-06-24T07:40:44Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-23/air-china-industrial-bank-zte-corp-china-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 3 p.m. close.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, added 57.96, or 2.2 percent, to
2,746.21. The  CSI 300 Index (SHSZ300)  rose 2.4 percent to 3,027.47.  Airlines:  Air China Ltd. (601111)  (601111 CH), the nation’s biggest
international carrier, surged 6.4 percent to 9.88 yuan.  China
Eastern  Airlines Corp. (600115 CH) advanced 4.6 percent to 5.21
yuan. China Southern Airlines Co. (600029 CH) jumped 7.8 percent
to 7.90 yuan.  Crude oil for August delivery dropped 4.6 percent to $91.02
a barrel on the  New York Mercantile Exchange  yesterday, erasing
its gains for the year. Prices were at $91.26 today.  Automakers: SAIC Motor Corp. (600104 CH) gained 2.9 percent
to 18.97 yuan, the highest close since April 14. FAW Car Co.
(000800 CH) increased 3.4 percent to 14.32 yuan.  The National Development and Reform Commission and other
government agencies are seeking to remove purchase limits on
vehicles, National Business Daily reported today, citing an
unidentified official at the China Association of Automobile
Manufacturers. Dong Yang, deputy head of the automakers group,
denied the report.  China Railway Construction Corp. (601186 CH) added 2.4
percent to 5.89 yuan, the steepest increase since Feb. 15. The
company said it won 10.3 billion yuan ($1.6 billion) of
contracts to build station-related projects on the new Jilin-
Huichun rail line. The value of the contracts is equal to 2.2
percent of 2010 revenue, according to a statement to the
 Shanghai Stock Exchange .  Chongqing Jiulong Electric Power Co. (600292 CH) rose 2.2
percent to 15.20 yuan, the largest rally since June 8. The
company got government approval for a private placement, in
which it plans to sell no more than 185.4 million shares,
according to a statement to the Shanghai Stock Exchange today.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net  